## 7. Interview-Ready Q&A

### Q: "What is this project about?"
> "Aegis is a customer support ticket management system that I built from scratch using the MERN stack. It allows customers to raise support issues, agents to respond in real-time via Socket.io chat, and admins to manage the entire system with analytics. It features JWT authentication with role-based access control, auto-incrementing ticket IDs, and a modern dark-themed SaaS UI."

### Q: "Why did you use Socket.io instead of just REST APIs for chat?"
> "REST is request-response — the client has to keep asking 'any new messages?' (polling). Socket.io uses WebSockets which maintain a persistent connection. When an agent sends a message, it's pushed to the customer's browser instantly. This also enables typing indicators. It's the same technology WhatsApp Web and Slack use."

### Q: "How does your authentication work?"
> "When a user logs in, the server verifies their password using bcrypt comparison, then generates a JWT token containing the user's ID. This token is stored in localStorage and attached to every API request via an Axios interceptor. On the server side, every protected route goes through authMiddleware which verifies the token and attaches the user info to the request object. For role-based access, a separate roleMiddleware checks if the user's role is in the allowed list."

### Q: "How do you handle different permissions for different roles?"
> "I use a middleware factory pattern. `protect('admin', 'agent')` returns a middleware function that checks `req.user.role` against the allowed roles. Routes are stacked: `authMiddleware → roleMiddleware → controller`. For data-level filtering, the same `/tickets` endpoint returns different results based on role — customers see only their tickets, agents see assigned + unassigned, admins see all."

### Q: "What happens if the JWT token expires?"
> "On the client side, the Axios response interceptor catches any 401 status code. When it detects one, it automatically clears the token and user data from localStorage and redirects the user to the login page. On the server side, the JWT library throws a `TokenExpiredError` which my error middleware catches and returns a clean error message."

### Q: "How are ticket IDs generated?"
> "I use a Counter collection in MongoDB with an atomic `findOneAndUpdate` operation using `$inc`. This runs in a Mongoose pre-save hook on the Ticket model. Each time a ticket is created, the counter increments by 1 and the ticket gets formatted as `TKT-{value}`. The atomic operation ensures no duplicate IDs even under concurrent requests."

